<subSubSection id="C3096576D550FF9CFF30F9BAFC5C66C8" pageId="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAC36FDD550FF9CFF30F9BAFC5C66C8" blockId="1.[151,1437,605,1746]" pageId="1">
<emphasis id="B967EAEFD550FF9CFF30F9BAFEF86600" bold="true" box="[199,314,1577,1602]" pageId="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C134D7ED550FF9CFDA1F9BAFC6D6600" authority="Chemsak, 1999" authorityName="Chemsak" authorityYear="1999" box="[598,943,1577,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janzeni">
<emphasis id="B967EAEFD550FF9CFDA1F9BAFD356603" box="[598,759,1577,1601]" italics="true" pageId="1">Phaea janzeni</emphasis>
Chemsak, 1999
</taxonomicName>
because of the middle leg with trochanters and the base of femora with a short acute tooth. However, the coloration patterns in both species are very different, 
<taxonomicName id="4C134D7ED550FF9CFF60F9E1FEC166CB" box="[151,259,1650,1673]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janzeni">
<emphasis id="B967EAEFD550FF9CFF60F9E1FEC166CB" box="[151,259,1650,1673]" italics="true" pageId="1">P. janzeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has black elytra, while the new species has dark-red elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3096576D550FF9CFF30F906FC386690" pageId="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAC36FDD550FF9CFF30F906FC386690" blockId="1.[151,1437,605,1746]" pageId="1">
<emphasis id="B967EAEFD550FF9CFF30F906FE8466EC" bold="true" box="[199,326,1685,1710]" pageId="1">Etymology</emphasis>
